ground_truth:
created attachment 9431720
monosnap django administration 2024-10-17 17-30-10.png

user agent: mozilla/5.0 (macintosh; intel mac os x 10.15; rv:131.0) gecko/20100101 firefox/131.0

steps to reproduce:

when i have a page (the one i'm looking at is password protected) with an iframe pointing at a pdf then i cannot print that pdf.

the html of the page can be as simple as (coming from django)
<form id="enter-field" action="/workflow/print-labels/" method="post" enctype="multipart/form-data">
    {{ form }}
    {% csrf_token %}
    <button type="submit">enter return</button>
</form>
<iframe id="pdf-frame" src="" style="width:100%; height:500px; border:none;" sandbox="allow-modals allow-forms allow-pointer-lock allow-popups allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-top-navigation"></iframe>.

i used all of the allows to hopefully reduce the possibility of errors.

i load that iframe with 
<script>
document.addeventlistener('domcontentloaded', function() {
    const form = document.queryselector('form[id="enter-field"]');
    form.addeventlistener('submit', function(event) {
        event.preventdefault();

        fetch(form.action, {
            method: 'post',
            body: new formdata(form)
        })
        .then(response => response.blob())
        .then(blob => {
            const url = url.createobjecturl(blob);
            var iframe = document.getelementbyid('pdf-frame');
            iframe.src = url;
        })
        .catch(error => console.error('error:', error));
    });
});
</script>

the pdf gets loaded into the iframe as expected.  i see the pdf viewer (as shown in the attached image).  clicking the download icon works as expected (dialog box to pick a location).  click the print button in the pdf viewer is unexpected.


actual results:

clicking the print button in the pdf viewer has no noticeable effect in the ui.  no print dialog in opened.  looking at the debug console i see:
uncaught ns_error_failure: 
    triggerprinting resource://pdf.js/web/viewer.mjs:12520
    dispatch resource://pdf.js/web/viewer.mjs:1332
    dispatch resource://pdf.js/web/viewer.mjs:1389
    bindlisteners resource://pdf.js/web/viewer.mjs:11179
    #bindlisteners resource://pdf.js/web/viewer.mjs:11177
    toolbar resource://pdf.js/web/viewer.mjs:11118
    _initializeviewercomponents resource://pdf.js/web/viewer.mjs:11712
    initialize resource://pdf.js/web/viewer.mjs:11508
    run resource://pdf.js/web/viewer.mjs:11773
    webviewerload resource://pdf.js/web/viewer.mjs:13615
    <anonymous> resource://pdf.js/web/viewer.mjs:13619


expected results:

i expected to see a dialog pop up asking me which printer to use.  then i expected that printout to be only the contents of the iframe.

steps to reproduce:

i use firefox 96.0.1 on linux mint (i also tested this behaviour with firefox 96.0.1 from https://www.mozilla.org/de/firefox/all/#product-desktop-release).
the option "pdfjs.enablepermissions" is enabled, even if it is disabled in policies.json on linux (when the "enabled: true" option is not used).

steps to reproduce:
1. set /etc/firefox/policies/policies.json to
{
  "policies": {
    "pdfjs": {
      "enablepermissions": false
    }
  }
}

2. start firefox (i used a new profile)

3. see about:policies#active that option is correctly recognized and set to false.


--- 
other possibilities to define:
when setting /etc/firefox/policies/policies.json to the following:
{
  "policies": {
    "pdfjs": {
      "enabled": false,
      "enablepermissions": false
    }
  }
}
the value "pdfjs.enablepermissions" in about:config is locked and true (as pdfjs is correctly disabled, this has no impact). this was just to test when this bug occurs, so you can easier find the cause.

setting the option "pdfjs.enablepermissions" in the preferences, correctly works as expected:
{
  "policies": {
    "preferences": {
      "pdfjs.enablepermissions": {
        "value": false,
        "status": "locked"
      } 
    }
  }
}


and setting /etc/firefox/policies/policies.json with "enabled": true, also works correctly:
{
  "policies": {
    "pdfjs": {
      "enabled": true,
      "enablepermissions": false
    }
  }
}



actual results:

check the value "pdfjs.enablepermissions" in about:config.
for me, this option is locked and true.
i also verified the permission with an example pdf (https://h24-files.s3.amazonaws.com/65073/161759-fduyc.pdf) and i cannot copy text.


expected results:

"pdfjs.enablepermissions" should be disabled, when setting it in the policies.

